<!--
VOICING PLAN:
- Verse (bars 1-8): Spare 2-note RH, 3-4 note LH open voicings. Gentle, reflective.
  - C: E-G in RH (open 3rd), C-G-E3 in LH
  - G: D-B in RH (open), G-D-G-B in LH
  - Am: C5-E5 in RH, A-E-A-C in LH (vi chord = grief/lament)

- Chorus (bars 9-20): Jubilant ascending arpeggios, fuller chords, high register.
  - Bar 9: Broken C chord rising C-E-G-C in both hands (arpeggio figure)
  - Bar 13: G chord widens from D4-G4 to B4-G5 (ascending sweep)
  - Bar 15: F adds F5 in RH; G adds G5 in RH — widest voicing
  - Bar 17: Peak — E5-G5 in RH, C1 pedal at bottom = C2 range span
  - Bar 18: F5 descends from peak, f3 in melody mirrored by F2 in pedal

NON-DIATONIC HANDLING:
- F# in melody (bars 7, melody only): harp plays diatonic F natural in accompaniment
- D7 (bar 7) → G (V): same function, keeps diatonic
- G#° (bar annotation in 4100) → B° (vii°): already handled in 4100 only

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- Bar 3: G7 tritone B4-F5 in RH, same B-F in LH (G2-D3-F3-B3) — V7 tension without chromatics
- Bar 16: G-Am-G7 inner voice: D5→C5→F5 in RH, smooth chromatic-feeling voice leading but all diatonic
- Chorus bars 9-10: E5 sustained in RH layer 2 while E4-G4-C5-E5 arpeggio unfolds in layer 1
- Final cadence bars 19-20: G7 (B-F tritone) resolves to C (C-E) — textbook V7-I

TEXTURE ARC:
- Verse (bars 1-8): Sparse, hymn-like. 2 RH notes, 3-4 LH notes. Reflective character.
- Chorus opening (bars 9-12): Arpeggio motion introduces rhythmic life. Ascending contour.
- Climax (bars 13-17): Full 3-note RH, 4-note LH. G5 reached in bar 13-15. E5-G5 peak bar 17.
- Resolution (bars 18-20): Descend from F5, through E5, to C5 final. Pedal cinches the root.
  The "down from the heights, He arose!" arc is complete.
-->
